04734nam a22009135i 9780271093130DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780271093130  a(DE-B1597)644588  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF378.E94bM44 2022 7aSCI0750002bisacsh04a153.9223/eng/202112161 aMehlenbacher, Ashley Rose, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Expertise :bCultivating Character, Goodwill, and Practical Wisdom /cAshley Rose Mehlenbacher. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (198 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction / Understanding Expertise -- t1 Habituating Expertise as Rhetorical Act -- t2 Expertise in Rhetorics of Science -- t3 Expertise, Psychology, and Memory -- t4 Professional Researchers on Expertise -- t5 Citizen Scientists on Expertise -- tConclusion: Cultivating Expertise -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a deep distrust of experts in America today. Influenced by populist politics, many question or downright ignore the recommendations of scientists, scholars, and others with specialized training. It appears that expertise, a critical component of democratic life, no longer appeals to wide swaths of the body politic. On Expertise is a robust defense of the expert class. Ashley Rose Mehlenbacher examines modern and ancient theories of expertise through the lens of rhetoric and interviews some forty professionals, revealing how they understand their own expertise and how they came to be known as “experts.” She shows that expertise requires not only knowledge and skill but also, crucially, an acknowledgment by others—both specialists and laypeople—that one is a credible authority. At its heart, expertise is a rhetorical construct, and to be persuasive, experts must have the ability to apply their knowledge and skills rightly—in the right way, at the right time, to achieve the right end. Ultimately, Mehlenbacher argues that experts apply their technical knowledge effectively and win others’ trust through acting prudently and cultivating goodwill. Timely, practical, and sophisticated, On Expertise provides vital scaffolding for our understanding of expertise and its real-world application. This book is essential for beginning the work of rehabilitating the expert class amid a politics of extreme populism and anti-intellectualism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aExpertise. 0aRhetoric. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aand society.  aarete.  acitizen science.  adeliberate practice.  aethos.  aeunoia.  aexpert performance.  aexpert.  aexpertise.  aexperts.  aknowing-how.  aknowing-that.  aphilosophy and rhetoric.  aphronesis.  aprudence.  arhetoric of expertise.  arhetoric of health.  arhetoric of science.  arhetoric of technology.  arhetorical account of expertise.  arhetorical studies.  arhetorical theory.  ascience communication.  ascience.  atechne.  atechnology.  avirtue ethics.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271093130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271093130/original  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK